# RSVP -> Google Sheets (server-only; read by the API routes under app/api/).
# Copy to .env.local for local dev; set the same three in Vercel project env vars.
#
# The spreadsheet needs two tabs:
#   Guests    (you fill): party_label | first_name | last_name | display_name | plus_one_allowed | is_kid
#   Responses (app writes): Timestamp | Name | Email | Yes/No? | Dietary Needs | Additional Messages | Notes
# Columns are matched by header NAME, so extra/legacy columns and column order are fine — but
# the Responses tab's header row must literally read exactly those 7 labels (case/punctuation as
# shown) for the app to read prior responses back (edit prefill + resubmission detection).
# A plus-one has no column of their own to link them to their host: their Name cell is written as
# "<their name> — guest of <host's name>", and read back the same way.
#
# Leave all three unset (or set RSVP_FIXTURE=1) to run the RSVP flow against an
# in-repo sample list without touching the real sheet.

# Service account address (the "client_email" from the downloaded JSON key).
GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_EMAIL=your-sa@your-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com

# The "private_key" from that JSON key, in quotes. Newlines may be literal \n
# (as Vercel stores them) or real — the route handles both.
GOOGLE_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END PRIVATE KEY-----\n"

# The long token in the target spreadsheet's URL:
# https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/<THIS_PART>/edit
GOOGLE_SHEET_ID=the-long-id-from-the-sheet-url
